context: <a2_0>St. John's<a2_0/> (/ˌseɪntˈdʒɒnz/, local /ˌseɪntˈdʒɑːnz/) is the capital and largest city in Newfoundland and Labrador, <a0_0>Canada<a0_0/>. <b5_0><b6_0><b7_0>St. John's<b7_0/><b6_0/><b5_0/> was incorporated as a city in 1888, yet is considered by some to be the oldest English-founded city in North America. It is located on the <a3_0>eastern tip<a3_0/> of the Avalon Peninsula on the island of <a1_0>Newfoundland<a1_0/>. With a population of 214,285 as of July 1, <a4_0>2015<a4_0/>, the St. John's Metropolitan Area is the second largest <b8_0>Census Metropolitan Area<b8_0/> (CMA) in Atlantic Canada after Halifax and the 20th largest metropolitan area in Canada. It is one of the world's top ten oceanside destinations, according to National Geographic Magazine. Its name has been attributed to the feast day of John the Baptist, when John Cabot was believed to have sailed <b9_0>into the harbour<b9_0/> in 1497, and also to a Basque fishing town with the same name.
